scRNAseq data analysis (EBs 7g): Mapping summary from CellRanger

Author: MarÃ­a Maqueda

13th May 2024

Scope

This document is to check the quality of the mapping performed with CellRanger tool from 10x Genomics. Specifically, visualization of the common mapping metrics obtained per library (sample) are considered.

Primary data

A total of six samples were library-prepared and sequenced by NovoGene Co, Ltd.Â Libraries were prepared using 10x Single Cell 3âv3 kit. Corresponding biological samples were delivered to IJC at the end of Octoberâ23 and sequencing data was received at the end of Februaryâ24. Samples are equally divided in two conditions, considering cells from mouse embryoid bodies (mEBs 144h) :

  • in wild-type (WT) condition (3x) and,
  • after activation of 7* specific genes (7g) (3x) identified by CRISPRa in an earlier project phase.

*Genes related to HSC development fate.

Methods

Visualized results in this report have been generated by CellRanger v7.2.0 (Zheng et al. 2017) in a HPC environment using Singularity v3.8.3. Specifically, cellranger count was executed per sample to generate the corresponding data matrices. Introns were included in expression quantification as recommended by 10x Genomics (See for additional information https://www.10xgenomics.com/support/software/cell-ranger/latest/miscellaneous/cr-intron-mode-rec). Samples were aligned to refdatagex- mm10-2020-A transcriptome provided as well by 10x Genomics.

Results

Barcode Rank Plot

All six samples were successfully mapped to reference. Following figure shows the Barcode rank plot per sample. This plot shows the distribution of UMI counts in barcodes plotted in decreasing order of their corresponding number of UMIs. All samples show a typical (and good) behaviour with a âcliff and kneeâ shape. This is indicative of good separation between cell-associated barcodes and barcodes with empty emulsions. For more information on this, check: https://cdn.10xgenomics.com/image/upload/v1660261286/support-documents/CG000329_TechnicalNote_InterpretingCellRangerWebSummaryFiles_RevA.pdf

Overall statistics

Following metrics, per sample, are visualized:

  • general values: estimated number of cells, mean reads per cell and median genes per cell.
  • related to mapping quality: reads confidently (uniquely) map to intergenic/intronic or exonic regions.
  • sequencing saturation

General values: cells, reads and genes

The estimated number of cells per sample is:

The average number of cells for the WT samples is 7894 cells, while for the g7 group is 7832 cells. Thus, the number of cells in both conditions is very similar.

The median genes per cell per sample is:

The average number of median genes per cell for the WT samples is 3848 genes, while for the g7 group is 3773 genes. Thus, the median number of genes in both conditions is very similar.

The mean reads per cell per sample is:

The average number of median genes per cell for the WT samples is 26952 genes, while for the g7 group is 28615 genes. Thus, the mean reads per cell in both conditions is very similar.

Mapping quality: Reads confidently map to intergenic, intronic or exonic regions

In this section, percentage of reads mapped to intergenic, intronic or exonic regions of the reference are shown. Reads mapping to intergenic regions may be associated to contamination of ambient RNA. In this analysis, this potential contamination is not quantified but, in general terms, a 5% of contamination rate is usual. Mapping to intronic regions may be associated to unspliced RNA or mature RNA with retained introns.

Previous graphs show very good mapping metrics for all samples, in fact, all of them behave quite similarly. Mapped reads to intergenic regions is contained (around 5%) and to genome is high (>86%). In general, for mouse we would expect >85% mapped reads to genome for a good experiment.

Sequencing saturation

Sequencing saturation is a measure of the fraction of library complexity that was captured during sequencing.

For this experiment, sequencing saturation ranges between 21% and 25%. Required percentages will depend on the objective of the experiment i.e. these values would not be sufficient to detect low/very low expressed transcripts.
